transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Scott, this is K.T. Gitterich, bud. How's it going?

Speaker 2: Good. How you doing?

Speaker 1: I'm grateful, bud. I woke up above ground, not beneath, if you know what I mean.

Speaker 2: Any day above ground is a good day to...

Speaker 1: That's my mantra, dude, right there. That is it.

Speaker 2: God blessed me with another day.

Speaker 1: Amen, brother.

Speaker 2: I say I'm not six feet in a hole when somebody's throwing dirt on top of me. I'm good.

Speaker 1: You're a badass, bro. You're a badass.

Speaker 2: I'm about six feet in the ground, man, and somebody's throwing dirt on top of me.

Speaker 1: Hey, you know what? We're in America, dude. What is there to complain about?

Speaker 2: I mean, we can complain all we want, but you just get up and grind, man,

Speaker 1: and you get the change that you want, bud.

Speaker 2: Don't just whine, you know?

Speaker 1: Yeah, don't whine. Just go get it done.

Speaker 2: Hey, bud, I'm going to take care of you, bud.

Speaker 1: Just correct me if I'm wrong, because I see that you're a VIP one,

Speaker 2: and you're a true blue, man. You're a real one. You're a real American.

Speaker 1: So I'm going to take care of you, and I'm a veteran, so I'll definitely take good care of you.

Speaker 2: Are you a veteran?

Speaker 1: Yeah, Bravo 18, bud. 18 Bravo, you know?

Speaker 2: Thank you for your service, man.

Speaker 1: If it wasn't for guys like you, we wouldn't have the freedom we got.

Speaker 2: Bro, I always say it's your welcome day when it rolls around, but you're very welcome.

Speaker 1: I'll do it again, but I've been rocked, bro. I've been rocked.

Speaker 2: Oh, of course.

Speaker 1: They helped me out here at Score Blue.

Speaker 2: They gave me a shot, and I was homeless during COVID.

Speaker 1: But anyhow, bud, I'm going to help you put a stop to this.

Speaker 2: Just help me confirm what I see is you were working with Dr. Riley Green,

Speaker 1: and she set you up as a VIP, and she wrote a script for the FDA-approved Pfizer,

Speaker 2: the white diamond pill, the AGV, I believe, and it's made in our Pfizer-Lazen front.

Speaker 1: But I do see that Dr. Green has ordered the pharmacy to send refills on her behalf.

Speaker 2: Do you want me to put a stop to that and you can get it when you want, bud?

Speaker 1: Well, when I first ordered all this stuff, I don't remember requesting.

Speaker 2: I don't pay anything. I don't like it.

Speaker 1: No, no, no.

Speaker 2: No, no, I'll set it up where you get it when you want, but I'll put a button for you,

Speaker 1: or you could just call me and just work with me, and I'll take care of you.

Speaker 2: All right, bud?

Speaker 1: Yeah, yeah.

Speaker 2: I'll do that for you.

Speaker 1: Yeah, and you can reduce it down to five pills at a time.

Speaker 2: When I call refilling, can I request a quantity as well?

Speaker 1: I'll see if I can adjust, but I think the minimum refill quantity is 10,

Speaker 2: but I'll set it up for you where you can click it, a button, at your leisure.

Speaker 1: All right?

Speaker 2: Okay.

Speaker 1: I'll do that for you now.

Speaker 2: Give me about a minute, bud.

Speaker 1: Can I ask you a question?

Speaker 2: Yeah.

Speaker 1: What nationality are you, and where are you from?

Speaker 2: I'm Chamorro.

Speaker 1: I'm from the Mariana Islands, like Guam, but my father's from Texas.

Speaker 2: He's a Green Beret.

Speaker 1: You sound like your dad, too.

Speaker 2: Thanks for your service, man, because my dad served.

Speaker 1: I appreciate it.

Speaker 2: My uncle served.

Speaker 1: I got a couple cousins that served.

Speaker 2: I didn't serve out of high school.

Speaker 1: My dad told me, you know, you're going to go.

Speaker 2: It's going to make or break you, but with my hot temper and quick fisted ass,

Speaker 1: he said you're probably going to wash out.

Speaker 2: No, but, you know what, bud?

Speaker 1: You know what?

Speaker 2: Jiu-jitsu, bro.

Speaker 1: After the service, for my mental health and my emotional regulation,

Speaker 2: every day there's not one minute where I don't feel like choking someone.

Speaker 1: But in jiu-jitsu, you can go there and you can actually choke someone

Speaker 2: and you won't get in trouble.

Speaker 1: Yeah, I never thought about that.

Speaker 2: That's how I was out of high school.

Speaker 1: Quick.

Speaker 2: Quick to fight.

Speaker 1: You can do jiu-jitsu if you're like 80, 90 years old, bud, and it's free.

Speaker 2: I mean, like you go there and they can't sue you or anything,

Speaker 1: and it's legal.

Speaker 2: You know what I mean?

Speaker 1: Yeah, absolutely.

Speaker 2: You can smother them.

Speaker 1: You can choke them, you know, and they'll be good to go.

Speaker 2: They all signed up for the same thing.

Speaker 1: Same thing, yeah.

Speaker 2: Yeah.

Speaker 1: I never thought about that.

Speaker 2: That's pretty cool.

Speaker 1: Sometimes you're the hammer.

Speaker 2: Sometimes you're the nail, but, you know, try to be the hammer.

Speaker 1: Yeah.

Speaker 2: Wish I would have done this when I was 18.

Speaker 1: I would have definitely served, man.

Speaker 2: Damn.

Speaker 1: No, don't worry.

Speaker 2: You can still do jiu-jitsu, but let me handle this, Scott,

Speaker 1: and I'll take care of you and I'll give you my extension when we get done.

Speaker 2: All right, bud?

Speaker 1: Yeah, appreciate it.

Speaker 2: Stand by.

Speaker 1: Thank you.
